    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Helping Pets of Abused</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By BARTH HEALEY</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Healey, Barth</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Town animal shelter in Huntington, Long Island, opens program aimed at protecting pets of victims of domestic abuse while victims seek long-term housing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The town animal shelter in Huntington announced a program this week aimed at protecting the pets of victims of domestic abuse while the victims seek long-term housing for themselves.</p>
        <p>The Suffolk County Coalition Against Domestic Violence estimates that up to 40 percent of the victims of abuse delay leaving the scene of violence because of concern about their pets.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The town animal shelter in Huntington announced a program this week aimed at protecting the pets of victims of domestic abuse while the victims seek long-term housing for themselves.</p>
        <p>The Suffolk County Coalition Against Domestic Violence estimates that up to 40 percent of the victims of abuse delay leaving the scene of violence because of concern about their pets.</p>
        <p>The shelter will allocate 10 pens for such pets, which can be left for up to 30 days, with an extension available up to 90 days. Councilman Mark Cuthbertson said at a news conference that Huntington is the first town to offer such a service.</p>
        <p>BARTH HEALEY</p>
        <p>IN BRIEF</p>
      </block>
